 <img src="../kamarpukur_7.jpg" style="width: 100%; height: 400px; object-fit: cover;">

        </div>

<br>

The next day we returned to Mr. Falguni's home where we were all too tired to visit anywhere. We spent the evening watching a movie together.

<br><br>

At the final day, we visited the birthplace of <a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swami_Vivekananda">Swami Vivekananda</a>. There we watched two short films, regarding his speech at the Parliament of the World's Religions and an overview of his life. This was followed by a visit to <a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorasanko_Thakur_Bari">Jorasanko Thakur Bari</a>, the birthplace of <a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabindranath_Tagore">Rabindranath Tagore</a>. The house has been restored and preserved so as to offer a glimpse into Tagore and his family, much like a museum. It featured a vast collection, showing his work, ideas and his visits to Japan, China, Hungary, US, which were put up in their respective galleries.
Unfortunately, we were short in time, and henceforth we had to rush through the hallways to atleast to get a glimpse of everything. Funnily, a security guard working there were watching us and then later remarked "You missed a lot of details and need to visit here again!".

